The error message is suggesting that you are trying to use a nonlinear operation in a linear constraint or objective. In this particular case, the division `(portfolio_mean(x)/portfolio_var(x))` in the objective function is considered nonlinear. To fix this issue, you can simply use the `@NLobjective` macro instead of the `@objective` macro.

Replace this line:

```julia
@objective(portfolio, Max, (portfolio_mean(x)/portfolio_var(x)))
```

with this line:

```julia
@NLobjective(portfolio, Max, (portfolio_mean(x)/portfolio_var(x)))
```

Additionally, replace the linear `@constraint` calls with `@NLconstraint` for the nonlinear constraints:

```julia
@NLconstraint(portfolio, portfolio_mean(x) >= rmin)
@NLconstraint(portfolio, portfolio_var(x) <= var_max)
```

So the modified function would look like:

```julia
function opt_portfolio_both(rates_of_return, rmin, var_max)
    portfolio = Model(Ipopt.Optimizer)
    set_silent(portfolio)
    @variable(portfolio, x[1:size(rates_of_return)[2]] >= 0)
    @NLobjective(portfolio, Max, (portfolio_mean(x)/portfolio_var(x)))
    @constraint(portfolio, sum(x) == 1)
    @NLconstraint(portfolio, portfolio_mean(x) >= rmin)
    @NLconstraint(portfolio, portfolio_var(x) <= var_max);
    optimize!(portfolio)
    objective_value(portfolio)
    weights_opt = value.(x);
    return weights_opt
end
```

This should resolve the error and allow the optimization to proceed. Make sure that Ipopt is imported before running the code:

```julia
using Ipopt
```

